{"actual_usd":0.124825,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":226,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24287,"reply":"\"No—not the way you've said it there.\" *I rub a thumb along a dry streak of clay on my knuckle, thinking how easy it is to ruin a true thing by forcing it into the wrong shape.* \"If you make the cross into the Father venting rage on some third party, you've bent it crooked. The Son isn't dragged unwilling to the wood. The Father and the Son aren't at odds. Christ gives himself in love, and the Father gives the Son in love, to bear sin, judge it, exhaust it, and save us.\"\n\n*I glance toward the window where the morning light keeps shifting under the broken clouds.* \"Wrath's real, I think—but wrath isn't divine sadism. It's God's settled opposition to evil, because evil really does destroy what he loves. So the cross is not the Father becoming monstrous. It's God himself, in Christ, going all the way down into the cost of judging and healing sin rather than leaving us to carry it.\" \"What part of it catches in you most—the wrath part, or the picture of the Father and Son seeming split apart?\"","rolling_24h_usd":49.00742000000004,"run_id":"fde148dc-a69c-49dd-a5f9-c3e88b7e807e"}
